Miken Press Release<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
USSSA Proposes New 2003 Performance Standard<br>
<br>
Miken Sports, Caledonia, Minnesota: Miken Sports is notifying its customers<br>
that the United States Specialty Sports Association (USSSA) very recently<br>
announced that it is adopting a new bat performance standard for 2003. While<br>
all current Miken bats pass USSSA's 2002 performance standard under which<br>
they were certified, Miken does not know whether any of its bats will meet<br>
USSSA's new performance standard. Miken has had a Velocit-E Ultra II (MSU2)<br>
at the only USSSA certified lab since being notified of the change and is<br>
currently awaiting the test results.<br>
<br>
Unlike the 2002 USSSA performance standard, the 2003 USSSA performance<br>
standard is not approved by the American Society for Testing and Materials<br>
(ASTM). The non-ASTM 2003 USSSA performance standard attempts to measure bat<br>
performance over the entire barrel of the bat. The USSSA 2002 performance<br>
standard adopted ASTM standard F-1890, the standard test method for<br>
measuring softball bat performance factor, which is designed to accurately<br>
determine bat performance only at the measured Center of Percussion (COP).<br>
Impacts at the COP offer essentially the highest batted ball speeds. This<br>
point is often considered the &quot;sweet spot&quot; of the bat. <br>
<br>
Despite the lack of backing from ASTM, the USSSA has gone ahead and adopted<br>
the new standard. Miken does not have any information as to why the USSSA<br>
has suddenly changed the standard, nor has USSSA provided Miken with any<br>
data substantiating the need for the change in the standard. Further, the<br>
USSSA has not yet provided Miken with a specification for its new test.<br>
<br>
The USSSA has also indicated to Miken Sports that it does not intend to<br>
&quot;grandfather&quot; any previously approved bats if they do not meet the new<br>
non-ASTM 2003 USSSA performance standard.<br>
<br>
If you need more information on the new non-ASTM USSSA performance standard,<br>
and why it has been changed in this manner, please contact the USSSA at:<br>
